    "opponent": "Usc Upstate",
    "result": "L",
    "boxscore_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/usc-upstate/boxscore/19756",
    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/18/baseball-charlotte-upended-by-usc-upstate-in-ninth-inning",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTE \u2013\nCharlotte Baseball erased an early 3-0 deficit to lead by as many as five over USC Upstate before the Spartans scored a pair of runs in the ninth to stun the Niners, 11-10, at Hayes Stadium on Wednesday (March 18).\nCharlotte (14-7) had a six-run second inning to erase an early 3-0 lead the Spartans (11-11) had built in the opening frame and put the Niners in front. CLT led until Upstate tied it in the seventh, with the Niners pulling ahead again in the home half of the seventh, until the visitors struck for two in the last. Charlotte had the tying run on third and the winning run at first with two outs to work with, but bounced into a game-ending double play to kill the rally.\nFor the third time this season, every 49er in the lineup recorded a hit as the team totaled 15 in the game, tied for the second-most hits in a single game this season for the Green and White. It's also the 14th time Charlotte has had double-digit hits in a game this year and the seventh time accomplishing the feat in the last nine games.\nCale Stricklin\nled the way with three hits in the game, notching his first three-hit game as a Niner.\nTodd Hudson\n,\nDawson Bryce\n, and\nDylan Koontz\n\u2013 the 2-3-4 hitters in Charlotte's lineup \u2013 all had a pair of hits in the contest, as did\nRobert Nedry\n. Both Hudson and Koontz hit home runs in the game, the second straight game with a homer for Hudson, while Koontz's drove in two of his team-high three RBIs in the game.\nSpencer Nolan\n,\nAlec DeMartino\n,\nCody Gunderson\n, and\nAdrian Jimenez\nall had a single hit on Wednesday to join the quintet of multi-hit performances.\nAdam Baker\nwas the first of seven pitchers to toe the rubber for Charlotte on Wednesday, with the staff collecting 12 strikeouts as a unit for the team's 13th game with double-digit strikeouts this season.\nAJ Camp\nwas the first arm out of the bullpen and he fanned two batters before handing the ball off to\nWesley Jones\n.\nSebastian Perez\nstruck out a season-high four batters in 3.0 innings after taking over for Jones, with\nChase Carson\nadding a K in the next 1.2 frames.\nJoseph Taylor\nreplaced Carson and added four punchouts in 1.2 innings while being saddled with the loss, one day after notching the win at South Carolina.\nRyan Combs\nfinished the final two outs off for the Niners, getting one of them on strikes.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nUSC Upstate opened the scoring in the first frame, using a pair of walks and a home run to take an early 3-0 lead.\nCharlotte's offense did not let the early score by the visitors go unanswered, rattling off the next eight runs in the game to take the lead, starting with a no-doubt two-run homer from Koontz in the home half of the first that was crushed 112 mph off the bat.\nA six-spot followed in the second inning, starting with a single to left from Stricklin to tie the game up. Gunderson drew a walk to begin the inning and moved up to third when Nedry doubled to the wall in the gap in left. Stricklin was the next batter and found the grass in left to bring home Gunderson and put runners on the corners. A grounder to third retired Stricklin at second for the second out of the inning, but the relay throw to first to try and get Nolan was late, allowing the inning to continue and Nedry's run to count.\nHudson was the very next batter and continued his red-hot streak at the plate, putting one into the trees behind Charlotte's bullpen in right to extend the lead. Bryce followed that with a triple under the scoreboard in right-center before coming home on a single from Koontz for the latter's third RBI of the game. The big inning wasn't done yet, wrapping up on a single from Gunderson through the left side of the infield to bring home Koontz from second.\nUpstate countered with a crooked number of its own in the third, bringing around three runs on a single, a walk, and a pair of doubles to make it a two-run ballgame, 8-6.\nBoth sides tacked on a single run in the fourth, with four hits in the frame scoring a run for the Spartans. USC Upstate tried to bring another run home earlier in the inning, but a perfectly executed relay from Nolan to Nedry to Stricklin got the runner at the plate following a single. Charlotte's answer in the home half came without requiring a hit as DeMartino walked, stole second, took third on a groundout, and then scored on a wild pitch.\nThe fifth inning was the first scoreless stanza for both sides in the game before the Spartans pulled within one with a run in the sixth after a pair of walks, a sacrifice bunt, and a groundout. USC Upstate pulled level for the first time in the seventh in similar fashion, using a walk, a sac bunt, and a double.\nCharlotte retook the lead after the stretch with a pair of singles and a couple of Spartan errors. Jimenez singled to start the frame and then took second on an errant pickoff attempt by the USC Upstate pitcher. Stricklin was the next batter up and singled to center, where the defender bobbled the ball, allowing both Niners an extra 90 feet, bringing Jimenez home.\nThe Spartans put the tying run on first after a lead-off single in the eighth, but Taylor responded with three straight strikeouts to leave him there. Another Upstate error allowed Gunderson to reach in the home half and he reached third on a groundout, representing an insurance run, but was left there.\nUSC Upstate broke through in the ninth, bringing a pair of runs around on three hits to tie the game and take the lead for the first time since the second inning.\nCharlotte's rally attempt in the last started with a single from the nine-hole hitter Stricklin, his third hit of the day. He was pinch-ran for by\nJohnny Sutryk\n, who moved into scoring position on a sacrifice bunt from Nolan. Hudson reached on a fourth Upstate error to put runners on the corners but CLT bounced into a double play one batter later to leave the tying run on third.\nUP NEXT\nCharlotte begins American Conference play this weekend with a series at Wichita State. The action begins Friday (March 20) at 7 p.m. ET and continues on Saturday at 3 p.m. ET and Sunday at 1 p.m. ET."
